## Config-driven (read this first)

Every path, project list, and project-specific name in this skill is derived from the runtime config file:

- **Config path:** `<WATCHTOWER_CONFIG_PATH>` (e.g., `C:\code\watchtower\watchtower.config.json` or `/home/you/code/watchtower/watchtower.config.json`)
- **Keys used by this skill:**
  - `portfolioRoot` — directory that contains every project folder
  - `watchtowerRoot` — Watchtower runtime repo root (where the dashboard, scans/, and helper scripts live)
  - `promptsRoot` — directory holding the methodology files (`security-scan-prompt.md` + `claude-md-template.md`). Optional. Defaults to `<watchtowerRoot>/prompts/`. Set this if you want the runtime to read methodology from a separate folder (e.g., a cloned copy of the public watchtower repo) instead of duplicating files into your runtime.
  - `commercialAppSlug` — slug of your paid app (used in Phase B.7 Step 3); look it up in `projects[]` to get `folder` and `displayName`. Set to `null` if you don't have one.
  - `exclusions` — folder names under `portfolioRoot` to ignore when sweeping
  - `projects` — canonical list of `{folder, slug, displayName, category, isCommercial?}` entries
  - `scanCadenceDays` — interval for Phase 0 self-rescheduling

If any other path or name in this file looks hardcoded, prefer the config value. See `watchtower.config.example.json` for a starting template.

The scan version (e.g., `v6.7`) is read dynamically from the first `v\d+\.\d+` match in `<promptsRoot>/security-scan-prompt.md` (or `<watchtowerRoot>/prompts/security-scan-prompt.md` when `promptsRoot` is unset). `phase_c_update.py` already does this and will fail loud if neither path resolves; the commit message in Phase D should quote the same value.

## Phase 0 — Self-reschedule the next run FIRST (before anything else)

**Run this BEFORE Phase A.** If the scan crashes anywhere after this point, the next run is still armed — that's the whole point of doing it first.

1. Compute the next fire timestamp: now (in your local time zone) + `config.scanCadenceDays` days, at your preferred run hour. Format as ISO 8601 with the correct offset for that future date.
2. Arm a one-time run of this skill at that timestamp, using the same scheduler that fired the current run (Claude Code scheduled run, a scheduled-tasks MCP, OS scheduler — whatever you installed with). Same mechanism in, same mechanism out: don't switch schedulers mid-chain.
3. If arming succeeds, log `"Next run armed for <iso-timestamp>"` and proceed to Phase 0.5.
4. If arming fails: do NOT proceed silently — emit a P1-equivalent warning in the final scan summary so the human notices. The chain is broken until manually re-armed.

**Why first, not last:** Putting self-rescheduling at the END means a crashed scan = dead chain. Putting it FIRST means the next scan always happens, even if today's scan was a total disaster.

**Why one-shot timestamps and not cron:** True N-day cadence isn't expressible in a 5-field cron when N doesn't divide cleanly into months. A self-armed one-time run gives exact spacing. The tradeoff is fragility — see paragraph above for the mitigation.

## Phase 0.5 — Sync local repos from remote (ff-only, before any scanning)

**Runs AFTER Phase 0 self-reschedule, BEFORE Phase A.** Two reasons this exists:

1. **Methodology freshness.** The scan prompt is maintained in the public watchtower repo. Syncing `promptsRoot` (or `watchtowerRoot`, if your prompts live inside it) before each run means every scan executes the current methodology version — prompt updates reach you automatically, no manual re-download.
2. **Code freshness.** If you push to a project from another machine (or CI commits to it), this machine's local folder is behind remote, and the scan would audit stale code and report an outdated posture as current — a false all-clear.

The sync is **fast-forward-only**: it never creates a merge commit and never hits a conflict an unattended agent would have to resolve.

> **Prefer to review prompt changes before adopting them?** Check out a release tag in your clone of the public watchtower repo instead of tracking `main`. The ff-only sync refuses to move a detached HEAD, so you stay pinned (it records `repo-sync-stale` for that repo — expected, ignore it) until you choose to update.

**Repos to sync:** every `config.projects` folder present at `<portfolioRoot>/<folder>`, plus `watchtowerRoot` and the repo containing `promptsRoot`. For `promptsRoot`, resolve the containing repo first — `git -C "<promptsRoot>" rev-parse --show-toplevel` — because `promptsRoot` is typically `<public-clone>/prompts`, a subdirectory with no `.git` of its own; syncing the subdirectory path literally would hit the no-op gate below and silently leave your methodology stale. (Syncing `watchtowerRoot` also keeps Phase D's push from being rejected as non-fast-forward, if your runtime pushes.)

For each repo path:
1. If `<path>/.git` is absent, silent no-op (not a repo).
2. `git -C "<path>" fetch --quiet` — read-only, never modifies the working tree.
3. **Dirty-tree gate:** if `git -C "<path>" status --porcelain` is non-empty (uncommitted local changes), do NOT pull. Record `repo-sync-skipped-dirty` and scan whatever is local. (Uncommitted WIP is current local work — scan it, just flag that it wasn't synced.)
4. Else `git -C "<path>" merge --ff-only "@{u}"` (keep the quotes — PowerShell parses a bare `@{u}` as a hash literal before Git ever sees it):
   - Advanced N commits → record `synced` + the commit delta.
   - Already up to date → record `clean`.
   - Fails (diverged history, no upstream, detached HEAD) → do NOT force, do NOT merge. Record `repo-sync-stale` with the reason and scan whatever is local. A diverged tree usually means a prior scan committed CLAUDE.md but the push failed — surfacing it is the point.
5. **Never fatal.** One repo's sync failure never blocks other repos, Phase A, or the rest of the scan.

Fold the results into:
- **Per-project flags:** any scanned project that returned `repo-sync-stale` or `repo-sync-skipped-dirty` gets a flag of that category appended to its `flags` array in Phase B, so the dashboard shows "scanned against possibly-stale local code" rather than implying a clean audit.
- **Phase D commit body:** a one-line sync summary, e.g. `Sync: 14 clean, 3 synced (+N commits), 1 skipped-dirty, 0 stale.`

**Why `fetch` → `status` → `merge --ff-only` instead of `git pull`:** plain `git pull` auto-merges (can create merge commits / conflicts) and gives no clean dirty-tree gate. This sequence is read-then-decide: behind → catches up cleanly; diverged or dirty → refuses and flags.

## Phase A — AI Tool Supply Chain audit (runs ONCE, before per-project scans)

1. Read STEP 1C from `<promptsRoot>/security-scan-prompt.md`.
2. Fetch threat-db.yaml and security-hardening.md from the FlorianBruniaux/claude-code-ultimate-guide repo.
3. Audit `~/.claude/` (global skills, plugins, MCP servers, hooks, memory files, settings, Claude Code version) and produce candidate findings (Phases 2-9).
4. Run Phase 10 NVD cross-validation on every `ai-mcp-cve` candidate flag and on every installed MCP/skill/plugin name. If `~/.claude/.env` defines `NVD_API_KEY`, send it as the `apiKey` query param for higher rate limits.
5. Write the result (including the `crossCheck` aggregate from Phase 10) to `<watchtowerRoot>/data/ai-tool-intel.js` — replace ONLY the block between `<!-- AI_INTEL:AUTO:START -->` and `<!-- AI_INTEL:AUTO:END -->` markers.
6. Capture project-level AI findings in a per-project map (keyed by project name) so per-project agents can append them in Phase B.

## Phase B — Per-project scans (parallel agents)

Iterate `config.projects`. Skip any project whose `folder` is in `config.exclusions`. Skip any project whose `category` is `"Archived"` (don't re-scan — last findings stay in `data/apps.js` from the prior scan, intentionally). Skip any project whose folder isn't present at `<portfolioRoot>/<folder>` (treat as a silent no-op, not an error).

**"Archived" contract:** archiving a project means "stop scanning it but keep the most recent findings visible on the dashboard." Phase B doesn't run scans for these. Phase C's `phase_c_update.py` iterates `config.projects` and looks for a scan JSON per slug — for Archived projects no scan JSON exists, so it prints `SKIP <slug>: no scan file` and leaves that app's entry in `data/apps.js` untouched. The `Archived` category in the dashboard has `excludeFromStats: true` and `dim: true` by convention, so the project still renders (dimmed) but doesn't contribute to aggregate P1/P2 counts.

For each remaining project:
1. Read the security scan prompt from `<promptsRoot>/security-scan-prompt.md`.
2. Run STEP 1, STEP 1B, STEP 2, STEP 3, STEP 4 against the project code at `<portfolioRoot>/<folder>`.
3. Append any per-project AI findings from Phase A to that project's `flags` array (categories prefixed `ai-`).
4. Update the project's CLAUDE.md between `<!-- SCAN:AUTO:START -->` and `<!-- SCAN:AUTO:END -->` markers with scan results.
5. STEP 4 of the prompt runs validation and emits `STRUCTURE: PASS` on success.

After all per-project agents return, write the per-project scan JSONs:

```
python "<watchtowerRoot>/scans/write_scan_jsons.py" --date <YYYY-MM-DD>
```

`write_scan_jsons.py` reads `watchtower.config.json` for the project list; do not pass it any other args.

## Phase B.5 — Validation sweep (single sequential agent)

After all Phase B agents return, run ONE sequential validator agent that reads each scanned project's CLAUDE.md and confirms the SCAN:AUTO block matches the canonical structure defined in `<promptsRoot>/claude-md-template.md`.

For each project, check between `<!-- SCAN:AUTO:START -->` and `<!-- SCAN:AUTO:END -->`:

1. `## Tech Stack` heading present, table includes Frontend / Backend / Data / Auth / Hosting / Testing rows
2. `## Architecture` heading present, with all four subheadings: `### Folder Structure`, `### Key Files`, `### Data Flow`, `### External API Calls`
3. `## Environment Variables` heading present (content can be "None — ...")
4. `## Security Notes` heading present, with all four subheadings: `### Active Flags`, `### Watch List (confidence < 0.8)`, `### Accepted Risks`, `### Resolved`
5. `## Guardrails` heading present with `### Universal (apply to all projects)` and `### Project-Specific`
6. `## Deployed Surface` heading present
7. `## Metrics` heading present with line counts, repo URL, production URL, last commit scanned, scan prompt version

Build a per-project pass/fail report. For each project that fails:
- Spawn a single re-scan agent for that project with explicit instructions: "Your previous SCAN:AUTO block was incomplete. Re-run STEP 3 + STEP 4 against this project. The validation found these missing or malformed sections: [list]. Re-emit the entire SCAN:AUTO block per the canonical template at `<promptsRoot>/claude-md-template.md`."
- Allow up to 2 retries per project
- After 2 retries, surface the failure in the final scan summary

Produce a final validation summary in the Phase D commit message body:
```
Validation: N/M projects passed structural validation on first attempt, X retries required, Y projects still failing (listed below).
```

## Phase B.7 — Codex adversarial pass (optional)

After Phase B.5 validates structure, optionally run a focused Codex second-opinion pass. The /codex skill is an OpenAI Codex CLI wrapper; it bills to your ChatGPT subscription (no per-call cost) and has three modes: review, challenge, consult. Skip this entire phase if you don't have /codex installed.

**Hard requirement: every Codex call wrapped in a 60-second timeout.** If Codex hangs on an auth prompt or rate limit, the scheduled task itself hangs — that's worse than skipping the second opinion. Use `timeout 60` in bash, or the equivalent.

### Step 1: Compute net-new P1 flags this cycle

1. Load this run's scan JSONs from `<watchtowerRoot>/scans/*-<today>.json`
2. Load the prior run's scan JSONs (whatever the previous date was)
3. For each project, compute the set difference: `current.P1_flags - prior.P1_flags` (compare by category + key text fragments, not exact text match)
4. Aggregate across all projects. Hard cap at 3 (sort by project criticality: the commercial app from `config.commercialAppSlug` first, then everything else; drop overflow).

### Step 2: Codex challenge per net-new P1

For each net-new P1 (max 3):
1. Build a self-contained prompt: the flag text, the category, the relevant file path(s) + line numbers from the scan JSON, and 30-50 lines of surrounding code context.
2. Run: `timeout 60 /codex challenge "<prompt>"`.
3. Capture stdout. If Codex disagrees substantively, record a `{project, flag, codexResponse}` entry.
4. If timeout fires or Codex errors, record `{project, flag, codexStatus: "timeout"|"error", reason}` — do NOT block the pipeline.

### Step 3: Codex review on commercial app's CLAUDE.md diff

Skip this step entirely if `config.commercialAppSlug` is null or the resolved folder doesn't exist.

1. After Phase B updates the commercial app's CLAUDE.md, stage the change but do NOT commit yet.
2. Run: `cd "<portfolioRoot>/<commercial-app-folder>" && timeout 60 /codex review` on the staged diff.
3. Codex's job: did Claude accurately describe what changed in this codebase, or did it hallucinate architecture details for files it didn't actually read?
4. Capture stdout. If Codex flags inaccuracies, record them.

### Step 4: Emit "Codex disagreements" section for Phase D

Build a markdown block for the Phase D commit message body:
```
## Codex second opinion

<For each disagreement>
- **<project> / <flag category>**: Codex disagrees — "<verbatim quote>"
  Claude's call vs Codex's call: [explain in one line]

<If Codex flagged the commercial CLAUDE.md diff>
- **<commercial app displayName> CLAUDE.md drift**: <codex quote>

<If no disagreements>
No Codex disagreements this cycle (N flags reviewed, commercial CLAUDE.md diff reviewed).
```

If Codex timed out or errored more than once, add: `Codex availability: N/M calls completed, M failures.` Do NOT block the commit on Codex availability — the scan still ships, just without the second opinion.

## Phase C — Dashboard update

After all scans + Codex pass complete:

1. Merge fresh flag data into the dashboard's APPS array:
   ```
   python "<watchtowerRoot>/scans/phase_c_update.py" --date <YYYY-MM-DD>
   ```
   The script reads `watchtower.config.json` for the slug→displayName map and extracts the scan version from the prompt file header. It writes to `data/apps.js`, not `index.html`.

2. Preserve any flags marked with `status: "accepted"` or `status: "resolved"` — the merger does this automatically.

3. lastUpdated dates are written by the merger.

4. Verify `data/ai-tool-intel.js` was written correctly by Phase A. Smoke test:
   ```
   node -e "global.window={}; require('<watchtowerRoot>/data/ai-tool-intel.js'); console.log(!!window.AI_TOOL_INTEL)"
   ```

5. Docs-freshness audit (v7.0) — deterministic script, one consolidated P4 `stale-docs` flag per project with findings (existing accepted/resolved stale-docs flags are preserved; projects that came clean get their active flag removed):
   ```
   python "<watchtowerRoot>/scans/check_docs_freshness.py" --merge
   ```

6. **Regenerate portfolio stats:**
   ```
   node "<watchtowerRoot>/scans/generate-portfolio-stats.js"
   ```
   The generator is idempotent and read-only — safe to re-run. If it fails, fix the input and re-run. The dashboard renders with stale `portfolio-stats.js` if the generator was skipped — not catastrophic, just out of date.

## Phase D — Commit and push

**Two runtime modes, pick the branch that matches yours:**

- **Private runtime repo** (the standard setup — data files tracked): follow all steps below. Every cycle's findings become committed history.
- **Plain clone of the public watchtower repo** (trial-run mode): your scan data (`data/*.js`, `scans/*.json`, `watchtower.config.json`) is gitignored by design — `git add` stages nothing. Skip steps 1–4 (the Watchtower repo commit/push); the dashboard reads the local files directly. Record `commit-skipped (public-clone mode)` in the scan summary. **Step 5 still runs** — the per-project CLAUDE.md commits are in each project's own repo, and skipping them leaves every project dirty, which trips next cycle's Phase 0.5 dirty-tree gate.

1. `cd "<watchtowerRoot>"`
2. Stage the artifacts the scan touched:
   ```
   git add data/apps.js data/ai-tool-intel.js data/portfolio-stats.js scans/*-<date>.json
   ```
   `index.html` is no longer touched by the scan — APPS lives in `data/apps.js`.

3. git commit with this message structure:
   ```
   Scheduled scan <date>: update flags + AI tool intel + portfolio stats

   Validation: <Phase B.5 summary line>

   <Phase B.7 "Codex second opinion" block from Step 4>
   ```

4. git push.

5. Also commit and push any CLAUDE.md updates in individual project repos. If those projects deploy via Vercel (or similar) on every commit, include `[skip ci]` in the per-project commit message — CLAUDE.md is local-only context and a deploy for that change is wasted build minutes. Format:
   ```
   <scan-version> security scan <date>: refresh CLAUDE.md SCAN:AUTO block [skip ci]
   ```
   (Where `<scan-version>` is whatever the prompt file currently says.)

## Phase E — Email debrief (optional)

Send a structured 5-section debrief to a configured recipient after Phase D. Pure quality-of-life — surfaces deltas and notable findings without you needing to open the dashboard.

**Skip entirely if** `config.emailDebrief` is missing OR `~/.claude/.env` doesn't define `RESEND_API_KEY`. `scans/send_debrief.py` handles both checks and exits 2 quietly.

**Runs whether Phase D succeeded or not.** If Phase D's commit/push failed, the email is still the most reliable channel to notify the human — surface the failure in the debrief and continue.

### Step 1: gather inputs

- This cycle's per-project scan JSONs at `<watchtowerRoot>/scans/*-<today>.json`
- The most recent prior scan JSON per slug (largest date < today)
- Phase B.5 validation summary, Phase B.7 Codex disagreements, Phase D commit hash + outcome, Phase 0.5 sync summary

### Step 2: compute deltas per project

- Net-new flags per severity: `current.P1 - prior.P1` (use category-level diffing for P1/P2 — minor wording changes shouldn't count as new)
- Resolved flags: flags newly marked `status: "resolved"` in this cycle
- Status flips: active → accepted, active → resolved, etc.

Aggregate across portfolio. Note projects with the biggest deltas (positive or negative) for "what stands out."

### Step 3: write the debrief (markdown, under 800 words)

```
# Watchtower scan <date> — <scan-version>

<one-sentence summary>

## What changed
- Net-new flags per severity across portfolio
- Resolved flags this cycle, grouped by project
- Status flips worth noting
- Phase 0.5 sync summary if anything wasn't `clean`

## What stands out
1-3 paragraphs on the most notable changes. Biggest delta, surprising regression,
Codex disagreement that survived, project that flipped to clean. Don't pad if
nothing stands out — say so plainly.

## What needs to be addressed
- Open P1s, commercial app first then alphabetical
- Open P2s, same sort
- Cap at ~15 items; if more, group by project

## What's good
- Projects with 0 P1 AND 0 P2 this cycle
- Projects that resolved flags
- Coverage wins: full lint+format, low CLAUDE.md hand-curated line count

## What's bad
- Projects with growing flag counts cycle-over-cycle
- Stalest scans (oldest lastScanned dates, excluding Archived)
- Missing CLAUDE.md or empty SCAN:AUTO block
- Codex disagreements that survived adversarial review

---
<Phase D commit hash + URL>
<Phase B.5 validation line>
```

### Step 4: send via Resend

```
echo "<debrief markdown>" | python "<watchtowerRoot>/scans/send_debrief.py" --subject "scan <date>: <N> active P1, <M> active P2"
```

The script reads `config.emailDebrief.{to,from,subjectPrefix}` from `watchtower.config.json`, loads `RESEND_API_KEY` from `~/.claude/.env`, converts the markdown to minimal HTML, and POSTs to Resend.

Exit codes:
- `0` — sent (record `email-sent` in scan summary)
- `1` — error (record `email-error`; do NOT block, the scan still shipped)
- `2` — skipped because not configured or no key (record `email-skipped`)

### Setup checklist for first-time use

1. Verify a sending domain in Resend (`alerts@yourdomain.com` or similar).
2. Add `RESEND_API_KEY=re_...` to `~/.claude/.env`.
3. Add this block to `watchtower.config.json`:
   ```json
   "emailDebrief": {
     "to": "you@example.com",
     "from": "alerts@yourdomain.com",
     "subjectPrefix": "[Watchtower]"
   }
   ```
4. Test before the next scheduled run: `echo "# test" | python scans/send_debrief.py --subject "test" --dry-run` (validates config + payload without sending).

## Important notes

- Read `watchtower.config.json` once at the start of each phase that needs it; don't hardcode any folder names in this skill.
- Use parallel agents for scanning multiple projects simultaneously (Phase B).
- The dashboard's stats filter is independent of `config.exclusions`. Excluding a folder means it isn't scanned; categorizing it as Other/Archived means the dashboard doesn't count it in aggregate stats. Both knobs exist on purpose.
- Quote any path with spaces in commands; never use `\ ` backslash-escape on Windows (triggers Claude Code security prompt regardless of allow rules).
- **Codex requires the /codex skill installed and the Codex CLI authenticated on the local machine.** The scheduled task runs as your session — if Codex auth has expired, the timeout wrapper prevents a hang but Codex calls will fail-soft.
- **If Phase 0 self-rescheduling fails one cycle, the chain is dead until re-armed.** Watch the dashboard's `lastUpdated` field — if it goes more than `config.scanCadenceDays + 3` days stale, re-arm manually the same way you scheduled the first run (e.g., tell Claude Code: "schedule a one-time run of the triweekly-security-scan skill tonight at 9pm").
